This instance already exists in another file (you touch the proof in this PR!)
Can you prove this in terms of `NNRat.addSubmonoid_closure_range_pow` or vice versa, by composing both sides with a map / comap by the coercion?

I don't see how because I can prove that `(closure (range fun x : α ↦ x ^ n)).map f ≤ closure (range fun x : β ↦ x ^ n)` if `f : α → β`, but that only tells me that `closure (range fun x : ℚ≥0 ↦ x ^ n) ≤ ⊤`.

In other words, the closure a priori gets smaller when I pass from `ℚ` to `ℚ≥0`, but it doesn't rule out any elements (because all elements are in it still)

I quickly hacked this together. As is it's not currently better than what's written, but perhaps it could be cleaned up into something nice.

```lean
import Mathlib

open AddSubmonoid Set Rat NNRat

@[simp] lemma addSubmonoid_closure_range_pow {n : ℕ} (hn₀ : n ≠ 0) (hn : Even n) :
    AddSubmonoid.closure (range fun x : ℚ ↦ x ^ n) = nonneg _ := by
  have h₁ := NNRat.addSubmonoid_closure_range_pow hn₀
  let coeRat : ℚ≥0 →+ ℚ := { toFun := (↑), map_zero' := rfl, map_add' := by simp }
  have h₂ := AddMonoidHom.map_mclosure coeRat (range fun x ↦ x ^ n) |>.symm
  rw [h₁] at h₂
  convert h₂
  · ext x
    simp only [mem_range, AddMonoidHom.coe_mk, ZeroHom.coe_mk, mem_image, exists_exists_eq_and,
      coe_pow]
    constructor
    · rintro ⟨y, rfl⟩
      obtain ⟨k, rfl⟩ := (even_iff_exists_two_mul n).mp hn
      simp_rw [pow_mul]
      use ⟨|y|, by positivity⟩
      simp
    · rintro ⟨y, rfl⟩
      exact ⟨y, rfl⟩
  · ext x
    simp only [mem_nonneg, mem_map, mem_top, AddMonoidHom.coe_mk, ZeroHom.coe_mk, true_and]
    refine ⟨(⟨⟨x, ·⟩, rfl⟩), by rintro ⟨x, rfl⟩; exact coe_nonneg x⟩
```
I managed to golf your proof down to five lines. I think that's good enough!

I'm slightly worried that this PR has increased import requirements in general, but maybe we don't care

I'll let @j-loreaux decide.

I think we don't care too much about this. I don't think we're using these `Star` instances (especially not the `StarOrderedRing` bits) very early in the hierarchy, are we? In fact, I haven't been aware of anything using this instance on `ℚ`. @YaelDillies, do you have plans to use this in many places?
I'm going to use those in discrete Fourier analysis, so that shouldn't be a problem
What was the reason for removing `simp` here?
`Submonoid.mk_eq_one` proves it (as reported by simp nf). It would be nice to have a `simpable` attribute that checks this.
Can you add a comment to that effect? Also, for consistency, either the new lemma should be called `mk_eq_one_iff`, or you should rename the existing one.
Why not put this in `Data/Nat/Star.lean` to avoid expanding imports?

because there's no meaningful difference between `GroupTheory.Submonoid.Basic` and `GroupTheory.Submonoid.Operations` right now (I tried to make sense of where it's split and couldn't find a sensible justification), so I don't think it's worth bothering using one instead of the other until that's figured out.
The new instances could go in `Mathlib.Data.NNRat.Star` to avoid expanding imports.
I think if the `Rat` instances are already here, the `NNRat` ones are fine to go next to them
(But probably the right thing to do is move both)
Yes, `Rat` and `NNRat` are very close in import weight (and will soon become even more so since I want to define `NNRat.cast`), so no point avoiding `NNRat` but not `Rat`
Is there a reason not to have `ℤ` here? It feels lonely and excluded. :smile:

```suggestion
  convert (AddMonoidHom.map_mclosure NNRat.coeHom <| range fun x ↦ x ^ n).symm
```
